# {{ .Name }}

{{ .Description }}

Generate and run a Go CLI tool built with Kong and zerolog.

## Usage

`{{ .Name }} example` runs the example subcommand included in the generated project.

Configuration can be loaded from the file pointed to by `--config-file`. The generated CLI currently supports these YAML keys:

```yaml
log_level: info
root_path: .
project_dir_prefix: ""
git_location: ""
```

Run `{{ .Name }} config` to generate a config file with the current defaults, then edit it to fit your environment.

Precedence is listed from lowest to highest:

1. built-in defaults
2. YAML config file
3. explicit CLI flags

Use `{{ .Name }} config` to inspect the fully resolved config after defaults and config-file loading have been applied:

`{{ .Name }} config`

`{{ .Name }} config` preserves environment-variable references from the config file. Commands can call `cfg.Normalize()` when they need normalized path values.

By default, `{{ .Name }} config` writes YAML to stdout. Use `--output` or `-o` to write it to a file instead:

`{{ .Name }} config --output /tmp/{{ .Name }}-resolved.yaml`

If the parent directories in the `--output` path do not exist, `{{ .Name }} config` creates them before writing the file.

Use `{{ .Name }} completion <shell>` to print a shell completion script for `zsh`, `bash`, or `fish`:

`{{ .Name }} completion zsh`

The zsh output defines `_{{ .Name }}`. To install it persistently in zsh, write it into a directory on `fpath`, for example:

`mkdir -p ~/.zsh/completions && {{ .Name }} completion zsh > ~/.zsh/completions/_{{ .Name }}`

The generated project includes:

- a thin `main`
- shared app config in `internal/appconfig`
- shared CLI runtime code under `internal/cli`
- shared injected args in `cmd/globals.go` with a default config path under `~/.config/{{ .Name }}/`
- a `go.mod` whose `go` version matches the locally available Go toolchain used to generate the project
- an example subcommand
- a shell completion subcommand
- a config inspection subcommand
- a Makefile with build, rebuild, test, vet, check, and clean targets
- smoke tests for help, version, and command wiring

## Common Commands

- `{{ .Name }} config` writes the resolved config as YAML to stdout or a file.
- `{{ .Name }} completion <shell>` prints a completion script for `zsh`, `bash`, or `fish`.
- `{{ .Name }} example` runs the example subcommand.
- `make build` builds versioned binaries into `bin/`.
- `make rebuild` forces a rebuild of versioned binaries.
- `make install` installs the current CLI.
- `make lint` runs `golangci-lint`.
- `make test` runs Go tests.
- `make coverage` runs Go tests with coverage output.
- `make coverage-html` generates an HTML coverage report.
- `make vet` runs `go vet`.
- `make check` runs linting, tests, and vetting together.
- `make clean` removes built artifacts from `bin/`.

## Tooling

The `make fmt` target expects these tools to be installed locally:

- `gofumpt`
- `goimports`
- `golines`

## Layout

- `cmd/{{ .Name }}` contains the binary entrypoint and command tree.
- `internal/appconfig` contains application config defaults, loading, normalization, and tests.
- `cmd/globals.go` contains shared injected arguments used by command handlers.
- `internal/cli` contains shared CLI runtime code for parsing, logging, and build metadata wiring.
- `Makefile` handles local build, install, and verification workflows.
